                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d238">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.7131/64a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany (<persName corresp="#p_SFM1" type="to"
                            >Sackett</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-21T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 21, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>54. Department’s 26, March 18, 4 p.m. The Legation at Bucharest reports that the
                    French and German Ministers there have informed it that the putting into effect
                    of the preferential clauses of the treaties in question is imminent. Please let
                    me know what action, if any, you have taken on the Department’s telegram under
                    reference and what was the German reaction. On March 21, <persName
                        corresp="#p_LR1">Leitner</persName>, of the German Embassy here, was told of
                    the substance of our telegram to you. He said he would inform his
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
